<subSubSection id="FA86A38895268887499108EEEAA33253" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="7967F369CF8F011BF92C2ED26943B6C4" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="146C93077143405380B349BC1357EBA7" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
<taxonomicName id="5724065432E56F540B1C788600DE35B8" baseAuthorityName="Alder &amp; Hancock" baseAuthorityYear="1864" class="Gastropoda" family="Discodorididae" genus="Platydoris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platydoris formosa" order="Nudibranchia" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="formosa">
<emphasis id="259FC7C4041931592881F9137A43C97B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Platydoris formosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from Australia (
<bibRefCitation id="483DD403C2AAD1F821D6D17ED365B7FB" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1071/RS16011" author="Nimbs, M" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Royal Society of Victoria" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="44 - 113" refId="B176" refString="Nimbs, M, Smith, S, 2016. An illustrated inventory of the sea slugs of New South Wales, Australia (Gastropoda: Heterobranchia). Proceedings of the Royal Society of Victoria 128: 44 - 113, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1071/RS16011" title="An illustrated inventory of the sea slugs of New South Wales, Australia (Gastropoda: Heterobranchia)." url="https://doi.org/10.1071/RS16011" volume="128" year="2016">Nimbs and Smith 2016</bibRefCitation>
), Tanzania, India, Indonesia, the Philippines, Samoa, New Caledonia, and Hawaii (
<bibRefCitation id="60E2DFFCE946A77E5FD60CBA16DBFC25" author="Gosliner, TM" journalOrPublisher="Sea Challengers Natural History Books, Gig Harbor" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" refId="B94" refString="Gosliner, TM, Behrens, D, Valdes, A, 2008. Indo-Pacific nudibranchs and sea slugs: a field guide to the world's most diverse fauna. Sea Challengers Natural History Books, Gig Harbor" title="Indo-Pacific nudibranchs and sea slugs: a field guide to the world's most diverse fauna." year="2008">Gosliner et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="9A2AB8F431FEB2C9AF88615F2FF26439" authorityName="Dorgan, Valdes &amp; Gosliner" authorityYear="2002" class="Gastropoda" family="Discodorididae" genus="Platydoris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platydoris cinereobranchiata" order="Nudibranchia" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="cinereobranchiata">
<emphasis id="D0A93D8CF8F0F445CE4F18ABCFD026D5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Platydoris cinereobranchiata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation id="9474E1F71DDDD119B8EF1DA6319A3B4A" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1463-6409.2002.00105.x" author="Dorgan, K" journalOrPublisher="Zoologica Scripta" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="271 - 319" refId="B64" refString="Dorgan, K, Valdes, A, Gosliner, TM, 2002. Phylogenetic systematics of the genus Platydoris (Mollusca, Nudibranchia, Doridoidea) with descriptions of six new species. Zoologica Scripta 31: 271 - 319, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1463-6409.2002.00105.x" title="Phylogenetic systematics of the genus Platydoris (Mollusca, Nudibranchia, Doridoidea) with descriptions of six new species." url="https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1463-6409.2002.00105.x" volume="31" year="2002">Dorgan et al., 2002</bibRefCitation>
is known from the Philippines, Australia, the Solomon Islands (
<bibRefCitation id="0931DE6C788A92677C56FC2B0B567523" author="Gosliner, TM" journalOrPublisher="Sea Challengers Natural History Books, Gig Harbor" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" refId="B94" refString="Gosliner, TM, Behrens, D, Valdes, A, 2008. Indo-Pacific nudibranchs and sea slugs: a field guide to the world's most diverse fauna. Sea Challengers Natural History Books, Gig Harbor" title="Indo-Pacific nudibranchs and sea slugs: a field guide to the world's most diverse fauna." year="2008">Gosliner et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
), and Indonesia (
<bibRefCitation id="60898E67A8F063A0A069C642770618FF" author="Yonow, N" journalOrPublisher="Zoologische Mededelingen Leiden" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="905 - 956" publicationUrl="http://www.zoologischemededelingen.nl/cgi/t/text/get-pdf?c=zoomed;idno=8504a17" refId="B287" refString="Yonow, N, 2011. Results of the Rumphius Biohistorical Expedition to Ambon (1990) Part 15. The suborder Doridina (Mollusca, Gastropods, Opisthobranchia, Nudibranchia). Zoologische Mededelingen Leiden 85: 905 - 956, http://www.zoologischemededelingen.nl/cgi/t/text/get-pdf?c=zoomed;idno=8504a17" title="Results of the Rumphius Biohistorical Expedition to Ambon (1990) Part 15. The suborder Doridina (Mollusca, Gastropods, Opisthobranchia, Nudibranchia)." url="http://www.zoologischemededelingen.nl/cgi/t/text/get-pdf?c=zoomed;idno=8504a17" volume="85" year="2011">Yonow 2011</bibRefCitation>
). Neither species has yet been documented in Thai waters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E9FCFB4A0AB84B7E3A2CCF580AD97F48" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="7B523FFF82518136A275C92CE2B99128" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FBDDBDA9455A59E13ED25CD4EFA31E3C" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
Externally, the specimens bear similarity to 
<taxonomicName id="A5104933CF800E38CDACE215990FAB78" baseAuthorityName="Alder &amp; Hancock" baseAuthorityYear="1864" class="Gastropoda" family="Discodorididae" genus="Platydoris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platydoris formosa" order="Nudibranchia" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="formosa">
<emphasis id="07EF31C9C7D44430A391053CCBF2D491" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Platydoris formosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as detailed by 
<bibRefCitation id="642C0F018EE1444D7EB969DBBB3C23EF" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1463-6409.2002.00105.x" author="Dorgan, K" journalOrPublisher="Zoologica Scripta" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="271 - 319" refId="B64" refString="Dorgan, K, Valdes, A, Gosliner, TM, 2002. Phylogenetic systematics of the genus Platydoris (Mollusca, Nudibranchia, Doridoidea) with descriptions of six new species. Zoologica Scripta 31: 271 - 319, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1463-6409.2002.00105.x" title="Phylogenetic systematics of the genus Platydoris (Mollusca, Nudibranchia, Doridoidea) with descriptions of six new species." url="https://doi.org/10.1046/j.1463-6409.2002.00105.x" volume="31" year="2002">Dorgan et al. (2002)</bibRefCitation>
although differ in numerous ways. The rhinophores of the present species are yellow to pale brown, sometimes with red spots near the apex, with no black spots between them. Rhinophores have 33-35 lamellae. The gills are grey with dark brownish red lines running along the rachises, with no black spots anterior to the gill sheath. A white ring is present around the rims of the rhinophore and gill sheaths. Most of the caryophyllidia covering the dorsum are a dark reddish colour with a few white patches randomly distributed. Larger bright red patches are more numerous and also randomly distributed across the dorsal surface. Ventrally white with large red spots which become more diffuse and concentrated towards the foot. Based on these characteristics, it appears that the specimens from Koh Tao bear characteristics of both 
<taxonomicName id="2B6CD4A770E7A615F59A903803FEDC05" genus="P." lsidName="P. formosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="formosa">
<emphasis id="213962B4BA7D896970EB2D87DFDBF435" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">P. formosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="DE1B158CA0A17EB810A1810A10918C78" genus="P." lsidName="P. cinereobranchiata" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="cinereobranchiata">
<emphasis id="B0D694B3DD6CE359228F1C7E9BD54CA8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">P. cinereobranchiata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
